    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Foliation: Modern foliation in pencil added, upper left recto; catchwords on every verso, lower left.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Layout: 11 long lines, border-ruled.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Script:  Written in naskh in black ink; pointed and vocalized. Burdah selections in nasta&#x2BB;liq in black ink; pointed.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Decoration: Polychrome headpieces in blue, yellow, gold, red, and green over text on first opening (f. 5v-6r); full page polychrome illustrations of the mosque at Mecca (f. 17v) and the Rawd&#x323;ah at Medina (f.18r); textblock is gold sprinkled and bordered in blue, red, and gold rules; gold roundels punctuate text. Rubrications in red. Page-opening ruled in blue and gold.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Binding: Lacquered red paper over pasteboard (Type III) with gilt paper inlays on a central medallion and two pendants on the vertical axis, with a blind stamped frame. The central medallion is embossed with the binder's name and a formula of humility: al-&#x2BB;abd al-h&#x323;aqi&#x304;r Haki&#x304;m Mulla&#x304; Khawa&#x304;jah Sah&#x323;h&#x323;a&#x304;f. Marbled paper doublure. Green leather spine.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Origin: Copied in 1295 A.H. (1878) (f. 126r).</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="520">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Collection of prayers for the Prophet Muh&#x323;ammad and other devotional materials such as a description of his tomb and lists of his names and honorary epithets, divided into 60 sections to be read daily over 2 months. This copy is preceded and followed by 91 lines from Bu&#x304;s&#x323;i&#x304;ri&#x304;'s poem known as al-Burdah (f. 1v-5r, 126v-130v) copied in nasta&#x2BB;liq. Includes a few marginal notes in Persian.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
